Revise, revise, revise; revision's the big, ugly trundle that makes writing difficult at all. Outlining is tricky for me, personally, but only because I suck at sticking to outlines that aren't more than a sequence of story beats. Of course, as some have come to learn, I suck in general. I'm neither of the above Anons, by the by.

Revision, that's where your biggest learning curve is. When you master revision, and can easily anticipate it and approach it without hesitation, you'll really find all you're missing are fresh ideas once you've committed to writing those stories that are the most vivid in your mind's eye right now. Don't worry a whole lot about perfecting your understanding of syntax and other sundry writing elements, that'll develop organically with practice, as well as after the impetus strikes to study for the sake of improvement. Just write.

I've been a colossal lame-o, I owe some outstanding critiques. I'll try to flog myself into it today.
